  "texts": [
    "During the medieval period, the notion of authorship was influenced by the dominance of the Church and the manuscript culture (Clanchy 1993).",
    "Works were often created by anonymous monks and scholars, and the idea of the author as an individual creator was secondary to the authority of the text itself, which was seen as divinely inspired (Minnis 1984).",
    "The concept of auctoritas, or the authority of classical and biblical texts, overshadowed the individual author (Irvine 1994).",
    "The late Middle Ages saw the practices of authorship increasingly attributed to individuals due to several key developments.",
    "The rise of universities fostered a more personal intellectual environment where scholars could gain recognition for their contributions (Ridder-Symoens 1992)."
  ],
